Reflection — Multimodal Property Price Prediction



🔹 What surprised me

The most striking insight was how visual features significantly enhanced prediction quality, even when strong tabular baselines already existed.

Traditional models achieved:
RandomForest → R²: 0.670
Multimodal model captured:
Visual quality (lighting, interior condition)
Spatial cues (room size perception)
Aesthetic factors not present in structured data

The model learned latent property quality signals directly from images—something impossible with tabular data alone.




🔹 Performance vs Baseline
Model	Type	R² / Loss
Linear Regression	Tabular	0.644
Random Forest	Tabular	0.670
Multimodal CNN	Image + Tabular	Lower validation loss (~0.64)

Interpretation:

Tabular models are strong baselines
Multimodal model improves representation richness
Gains are more visible in complex cases (luxury vs average homes)




🔹 Multimodal vs Single Modality
🧾 Tabular-only

Strengths:

Stable
Interpretable
Strong baseline performance

Limitations:

Cannot capture visual quality
Misses subjective property appeal
🖼 Image-only

Strengths:

Captures aesthetics
Learns implicit features

Limitations:

Ignores location, amenities, structured attributes
🔗 Multimodal (Your Model)

Key advantage:

Combines objective (tabular) + subjective (visual) signals

This is the real-world production setup used in:

Airbnb
Zillow




🔹 Training Insights
Strong convergence from:
Train Loss: 31 → <1
Val Loss: 4.15 → 0.64
Consistent improvement until late epochs
Minor fluctuations → expected in multimodal learning

Best model checkpointing was critical to avoid late-stage overfitting.




🔹 What failed (important honestly)
❌ 1. Diminishing returns after epoch ~15
Improvements slowed
Risk of overfitting increased
❌ 2. Data size limitation (~2K samples)
Deep models typically require much larger datasets
Visual feature learning constrained
❌ 3. Weak rare-category learning

From classification:

“shared” class had low recall
Severe imbalance issue
❌ 4. Image quality variance
Inconsistent resolution / lighting
Introduced noise in training




